		<header>
			
			<h1>EC Commissioner calls for a new generation of fisheries agreements </h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC Fisheries Commissioner, Maria Damanaki, recently convened a ministerial conference on the future of FPAs. Fisheries ministers of EU member states were present, as well as 17 ministers from Africa, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean and Greenland. This event provided an opportunity to exchange views on several issues related to sustainable fishing in third-country waters, including the need to develop a governance framework and to make financial support effective in developing the fishing sectors of third countries.</p><p>In her speech the Commissioner highlighted first the issue of conservation: ‘One problem we have identified is that we cannot always be sure to be fishing exclusively “surplus” resources. This rule addresses at the same time the priority that is due to local fisheries and the imperative of conservation. To establish how much surplus there is, or how much can be sustainably fished from it, we need to know two things: we need to know the state of the stock and we need to know if others are drawing from that stock. This evaluation has not always been performed in the past; but in our mutual interest we have to make sure that both scientific knowledge and transparency are a strict requirement for each negotiation’.</p><p>She also emphasised that a key element of the partnership is governance: ‘it is essential that our own fishing takes place within a high-quality governance framework. Compliance with the rules is clearly part and parcel of that – and when I talk of compliance I mean both on the part of our partner countries and on the part of our own EU vessels. I would like to hear your views on how to prevent people from trying to circumvent the rules by reflagging vessels, for example’.</p><p>Finally, she highlighted the fact that, today, given the benefits obtained, ‘the level of contribution of the industry is quite low compared to the contribution from the EU budget. We want to redress this imbalance, adopting a more modern and market-oriented approach for the payment of access rights’. To underpin these efforts, we want to restructure a third fundamental area: the shape and nature of our financial support … Let’s bear in mind that there are two levels to consider here: on one hand we need to tailor our support to the actual needs and absorption capacity of each of your countries, perhaps linking each sum granted to the achievement of specific objectives. This is in fact one of the novelties that the reform will introduce: payments should be linked to results. On the other hand we need to consider the synergies between the fisheries support we are talking about here and all other forms of assistance your countries may receive from the EU, for instance under the development policies. Again, it would probably be a good idea to channel all these funds towards measurable objectives and improve the mechanism for monitoring and delivery’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Web page of the Fisheries Commissioner, ‘Working towards a new generation of fisheries partnership agreements’, undated<br />

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/commission_2010-2014/damanaki/headlines/press-releases/2011/05/20110512_en.htm" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/commission_2010-2014/damanaki/headlines/press-releas...</a><br />
Speech by the Fisheries Commissioner at the ministerial meeting on ‘The future of fisheries partnership agreements’ Brussels, 13 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/11/332&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/11/332&am...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is interesting to note that the Commissioner does not question the existence of FPAs. This highlights the fact that, on the EC side, although it is accepted that they need to be improved in several aspects, it is seen that having an FPA in place facilitates the dialogue for the development of sustainable fisheries. But the ending of FPAs, as some observers are advocating, would not solve the issues linked to the activities of EU fishing vessels. It is also interesting to note that the Commissioner is pleading for a market-oriented approach for the payment of access rights by EU operators. That presupposes that there is transparency, not only concerning who gets access to a given fishery, but also concerning how much is paid for this access. Otherwise it will not be possible to determine what the ‘market price’ of access that should be paid by EU operators actually is, a pre-requisite for such a market-oriented approach.</p>
		</div>
		
